;being the leader&quot;, etc. while the younger one will get used to being told to &quot;do better&quot;, have lower expectations of him, etc. &#10;The book says that this persists through life. The article says &quot;Most research clearly shows that any gaps in levels of success between younger and older children are usually bridged by the third grade.&quot; &#10;I wonder which is right."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="660" language="en" documentId="5362" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Gladwell Outliers" date="November 12, 2012 at 10:44 am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://schoolsofthought.blogs.cnn.com/2012/11/12/my-view-kindergarten-redshirting-different-for-each-child/comment-page-1" topic="redshirting" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="5362" notes="" title="My View: Kindergarten redshirting different for each child"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="430"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="431" end="635"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="636" end="660"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>